<taxonomicName authorityName="FIEBER, WITH" authorityYear="1858" box="[122,292,476,499]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Plagiognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="253" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[122,292,476,499]" italics="true" pageId="253" pageNumber="254">Plagiognathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
leaves the placement of this species from 
<collectingRegion box="[291,385,505,528]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="253" pageNumber="254">Arizona</collectingRegion>
in question. Because the 
<typeStatus box="[167,217,534,557]" pageId="253" pageNumber="254">type</typeStatus>
is a female, and because my studies so far have provided no obvious association with males that can be dissected, it is difficult to say what the affinities of this rather nondescript, pale species may be.
